Reading your post just gave me a flashback to my teenage years. I brought my boyfriend to church with me one Sunday, which also happened to be a Sunday we were receiving communion, and I will never forget his reaction to the Lord's Supper.  This was a guy who had no previous church experience, let alone witnessing the communion service.<br>
<br>
As we held our pieces of bread and little cups of grape juice and the pastor said [paraphrase] 'Jesus said, this is my body, broken for you, take and eat....and likewise with the cup, this is my blood, shed for you, take and drink'   ..my boyfriend bolted upright in the pew and looked with bewilderment at the entire church..turning around in his seat to do so.  I think he would have run for the door if he had known where it was!<br>
<br>
So, even though I come from a similar background, and have viewed communion in 'remembrance' and as symbolic, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>to others</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, just knowing that this symbolism of bread...is Christ's body and we are asked to eat it, and likewise with the wine/grape juice as Christ's blood...I wonder why THAT never seemed just as ghoulish?  then again..it's tough I think to gain a broader perspective of how we might have viewed it before becoming a Christian. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=oneandonlyfemme>One and Only Femme</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://pages.prodigy.net/indianahawkeye/newpage24/15.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Keymaster of Disneyland</span><br>  Posts: 78<br> <font color=#B87333>(6/28/03 8:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://64.38.119.228/animgall/people/women/heads/victlady.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Eucharist</span><hr size=1> &lt;So, even though I come from a similar background, and have viewed communion in 'remembrance' and as symbolic, to others, just knowing that this symbolism of bread...is Christ's body and we are asked to eat it, and likewise with the wine/grape juice as Christ's blood...I wonder why THAT never seemed just as ghoulish?&gt;<br>
